2. Bronze Layer Schema
Bronze preserves the source structure almost as-is, but adds technical metadata useful for lineage, debugging, and audit.
2.1 Bronze Orders schema
{
  "order_id": "string",
  "customer_id": "string",
  "product_id": "string",
  "order_date": "string",
  "quantity": "integer",
  "unit_price": "double",
  "order_status": "string",
  "source_file_name": "string",
  "ingestion_timestamp": "timestamp",
  "load_date": "string",
  "pipeline_run_id": "string"
}

2.2 Bronze Products schema
{
  "product_id": "string",
  "product_name": "string",
  "category": "string",
  "brand": "string",
  "source_file_name": "string",
  "ingestion_timestamp": "timestamp",
  "load_date": "string",
  "pipeline_run_id": "string"
}

Why Bronze looks like this
Bronze should:
preserve source values
avoid heavy transformations
capture metadata about ingestion
So here we do not deeply clean the data yet.

3. Silver Layer Schema
Now Silver will have only:
one curated table
one rejected table

3.1 Silver Orders Curated schema
This table includes:
cleaned data
standardized data
derived columns
product enrichment columns
{
  "order_id": "string",
  "customer_id": "string",
  "product_id": "string",
  "product_name": "string",
  "category": "string",
  "brand": "string",
  "order_timestamp": "timestamp",
  "order_date": "date",
  "quantity": "integer",
  "unit_price": "double",
  "order_amount": "double",
  "order_status": "string",
  "load_date": "string",
  "pipeline_run_id": "string"
}

3.2 Meaning of each column in orders_curated
Business/source columns
order_id
customer_id
product_id

Enrichment columns
product_name
category
brand

Standardized date/time columns
order_timestamp → converted from raw string to timestamp
order_date → extracted business date

Cleaned numeric columns
quantity
unit_price

Derived column
order_amount = quantity * unit_price

Standardized status
order_status → usually lowercase like completed, pending, cancelled

Technical columns
load_date
pipeline_run_id

3.3 Silver Rejected Orders schema
This is used to store invalid records rejected during Silver transformation.
{
  "raw_record": "string",
  "rejection_reason": "string",
  "source_file_name": "string",
  "load_date": "string",
  "pipeline_run_id": "string"
}

3.4 Meaning of each column in rejected_orders
raw_record → full original row stored as JSON string
rejection_reason → why the row failed validation
source_file_name → which file it came from
load_date → partition/date reference
pipeline_run_id → audit tracking
Example rejection reasons
NULL_ORDER_ID
INVALID_QUANTITY
INVALID_UNIT_PRICE
INVALID_ORDER_DATE

4. Gold Layer Schema
Gold contains business-ready aggregated tables.
4.1 Gold Daily Product Sales schema
{
  "order_date": "date",
  "product_id": "string",
  "product_name": "string",
  "category": "string",
  "total_orders": "integer",
  "total_quantity": "integer",
  "total_sales": "double"
}

4.2 Meaning
This table is useful for:
daily reporting
product-level analysis
dashboarding
sales trend analysis

4.3 Gold Category Sales schema
{
